## Overview

This file is the single source of truth for the project's visual identity. Every UI
surface — landing pages, dashboards, marketing site, mobile app — derives its tokens
from the YAML front-matter above and respects the rationale below. Coding agents read
this file before generating any frontend code, and the design gate
(`tools/design_gate.py`) reads it before letting a visual surface be declared done.

## Aesthetic Family

`aesthetic_family` is the first decision, and every other decision on this page is
downstream of it. It is declared, not implied. This template declares **F3 — Warm
Editorial**: a serif body on cream with a single terracotta accent, for products that
should feel made by people rather than assembled by a framework.

If your product is a developer tool, a dashboard, or a statement piece, F3 is the
wrong family and the tokens below are the wrong tokens. Run the three-question picker
in CDIO-06 sec. 2 and replace them. Changing the accent hex while leaving `F3` in
place is how a design system quietly becomes a default again.

## Colors

Warm neutrals with one evocative accent. Temperature is the character here: cream and
clay carry it, and a cool grey would erase it.

- **Primary (#191817):** clay-black for headlines and core text. Permanence, readability.
- **Secondary (#6b665f):** warm slate for utility — borders, captions, metadata. Never competes with primary.
- **Accent (#c96442):** terracotta, reserved for interaction — primary CTAs, links, focus rings. Exactly one accent hue survives; a second is indecision (CDIO-06 sec. 3, rule 2).
- **Neutral (#f4f3ee):** the page ground. Cream, not white — the single largest carrier of warmth on the page.
- **Error (#a33a28):** state semantics only. Desaturated so it belongs to this palette instead of shouting over it. Do not repurpose for branding.

Contrast: every color used as text must clear WCAG AA (≥ 4.5:1 body, ≥ 3:1 large text).
This is a floor, not a target, and it is not arbitrable against character (CDIO-06 sec. 3, rule 5).

## Typography

Three families, each with a job: **Instrument Serif** for display, **Lora** for body,
**Work Sans** for UI chrome, plus **JetBrains Mono** where code appears.

- **Headlines (h1, h2):** Instrument Serif at regular weight. Editorial authority without institutional stiffness; the low weight at large sizes is the restraint that keeps it from shouting.
- **Body (body-md):** Lora at 17px. A serif body is the F3 commitment — it is what makes long-form reading feel like reading rather than scanning.
- **Labels (label-sm):** Work Sans medium at 13px with positive tracking, for metadata, captions, and form helpers. The one place a grotesque earns its place: chrome should recede.
- **Mono:** JetBrains Mono at 14px for code and tabular data.

Line-height contracts as size grows (1.05 at h1, 1.65 at body) — a deliberate hierarchy signal.

No default-tier font stack (Inter, Roboto, Arial, system-ui) appears here, because F3
does not sanction one. Three of the nine families do sanction Inter, deliberately and
for stated reasons; F3 is not among them. Inheriting a framework's font is not a
typographic decision, and `check_font_stack` will fail it.

## Layout

Strict 8px grid; every spacing token is a multiple of 4px. Page max-width `min(1280px, 92vw)`.
Section rhythm: `xl` (32px) between top-level sections, `lg` (24px) within a section.
Nesting depth is capped at two semantic levels — stacked padding with no semantic
purpose is the container-soup fingerprint (CDIO-06 sec. 4).

## Elevation & Depth

Depth comes from tonal layers and borders, not heavy shadows. The default surface sits
on the cream ground; elevated surfaces use the off-white surface token with a 1px
secondary border at 12% opacity.

## Shapes

Architectural softness — `md` (8px) for buttons, inputs, cards. `lg` (12px) for hero
panels. `full` reserved for avatars and pill badges only. Sharp corners are forbidden
on interactive surfaces.

## Motion

Motion clarifies flow; it does not decorate. One well-orchestrated entrance with
staggered reveals beats scattered micro-interactions. Hover, focus, and active states
must all feel designed — an interactive element with no considered focus state is an
accessibility failure, not a styling omission. No animated status indicators.

## Components

Component tokens reference primitives via `{path.to.token}` — never hardcode a color at
the component level. State variants suffix the component name (`-hover`, `-active`,
`-disabled`).

## Do's and Don'ts

- Do declare `aesthetic_family` before writing a single token.
- Do use the accent for the single most important action per screen.
- Don't mix rounded and sharp corners in one view.
- Do maintain WCAG AA contrast for all text — the floor is not tradeable.
- Don't use more than two font families in a single viewport.
- Don't inherit a font from a framework and call it a choice.
